+Close/retire has a durable recovery contract before any caller delegates:
+
+1. The close command either preserves all release lookup keys on the closed bead
+   until release is proven, or writes a transitional close fact such as
+   `state=closing`, `close_generation`, `close_started_at`,
+   `work_release_pending=true`, and a release identity snapshot before clearing
+   live identity fields.
+2. The scanner is a named controller/reconciler helper, initially owned by the
+   `cmd/gc/session_beads.go` work-release path or its extracted successor. It
+   runs synchronously after successful close when facts are complete, and again
+   on every controller/reconciler scan while `work_release_pending` remains.
+3. The scanner releases only open or in-progress work matching the persisted
+   close generation, bead ID, configured identity, session name, or historical
+   names allowed by `REQUIREMENTS.md`. A partial work query records
+   `durable-scan-deferred` and leaves release pending.
+4. Identity retirement and binding cleanup may clear current identity fields
+   only after work release converges, or when a persisted release snapshot is
+   sufficient for future scans. A newer `instance_token`, close generation, or
+   canonical named-session successor suppresses stale cleanup and prevents old
+   assignment keys from releasing successor-owned work.
+5. Crash-after-close-commit, skipped event emission, duplicate scanner pass,
+   partial-query retry, stale-successor, and terminal identity-retirement tests
+   are required before external close, retire, or sweep paths use the new
+   command.
+
 | Operation | Required order | Recovery authority | Subscriber class |
 |---|---|---|---|
 | Explicit wake request | validate -> commit wake metadata -> optional event/trace -> reconciler scan starts runtime | Durable wake metadata and controller scan | critical retryable |
